### TaskHub — gRPC request collection (Session 3)
# IntelliJ HTTP Client "GRPC" requests. Method discovery uses server reflection,
# which is enabled in notification-service's dev profile only.
#
# Prerequisites:
#   1. docker compose up -d postgres
#   2. ./mvnw -pl notification-service spring-boot:run   → gRPC on :9090
#   3. ./mvnw -pl taskhub-api spring-boot:run            → REST on :8080
#   4. Run "Login" in api.http first — it captures the JWT into {{auth_token}},
#      which is shared with this file. Every call below propagates that same token
#      as `authorization` metadata, exactly as taskhub-api does.
#
# The contract lives in taskhub-proto/src/main/proto/notification.proto.
#
# Note the quotes around task_id / project_id / assignee_id below: proto3's JSON mapping
# renders 64-bit integers as strings, because a JSON number cannot hold int64 without
# losing precision. That is also why the streamed events come back as "task_id": "16".

# The `grpc://` scheme is not optional here: it is what makes the call plaintext (h2c).
# Connect with `grpcs://` — or let the IDE decide — and the TLS handshake hits a server
# that only speaks plaintext, which fails with "HTTP/2 client preface string missing or
# corrupt" on the server side (the hex dump in that log starts with 1603 01, a TLS
# ClientHello). The server survives it; the call does not. TLS arrives with the
# deployment slices; until then every environment here is plaintext.
@grpcHost = grpc://localhost:9090
@token = {{auth_token}}

# Set after running "Create a project" in api.http; 0 subscribes to every project.
@project = {{projectId}}


### ── Discovery ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

### List the services this server exposes (via reflection)
GRPC {{grpcHost}}/

### Describe the notification service
GRPC {{grpcHost}}/taskhub.notification.v1.NotificationService/


### ── SubscribeTaskEvents — server-streaming ───────────────────────────────
#
# Start this FIRST and leave it running: it stays open and prints events as they
# arrive. Then create/update/delete a task in api.http and watch them land here.
# `project_id: 0` means "every project".

### Subscribe to one project's events
GRPC {{grpcHost}}/taskhub.notification.v1.NotificationService/SubscribeTaskEvents
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}
X-Correlation-Id: my-subscriber

{
  "project_id": "{{project}}"
}

### Subscribe to every project's events
GRPC {{grpcHost}}/taskhub.notification.v1.NotificationService/SubscribeTaskEvents
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

{
  "project_id": "0"
}


### ── NotifyTaskEvent — unary ──────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# taskhub-api sends this on every task mutation. Calling it by hand is a quick way
# to prove fan-out: `delivered_to` in the ack is how many open subscriptions got it.

### Publish a task event by hand
GRPC {{grpcHost}}/taskhub.notification.v1.NotificationService/NotifyTaskEvent
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}
X-Correlation-Id: my-trace

{
  "event_id": "manual-1",
  "type": "TASK_CREATED",
  "task_id": "1",
  "project_id": "{{project}}",
  "title": "Draft homepage copy",
  "status": "TODO",
  "assignee_id": "1",
  "actor": "alice"
}


### ── Negative / auth checks ───────────────────────────────────────────────

### No token → expect UNAUTHENTICATED
GRPC {{grpcHost}}/taskhub.notification.v1.NotificationService/NotifyTaskEvent

{
  "event_id": "forged",
  "type": "TASK_CREATED",
  "task_id": "1",
  "project_id": "1"
}

### Forged token → expect UNAUTHENTICATED
GRPC {{grpcHost}}/taskhub.notification.v1.NotificationService/NotifyTaskEvent
Authorization: Bearer not-a-real-jwt

{
  "event_id": "forged",
  "type": "TASK_CREATED",
  "task_id": "1",
  "project_id": "1"
}

### Health check — exempt from auth, so probes keep working without a token
GRPC {{grpcHost}}/grpc.health.v1.Health/Check

{}


### ── The same calls with grpcurl ──────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Every line below is a comment — grpcurl speaks plaintext with -plaintext, so there is
# no scheme to get wrong. Copy them into a terminal.
#
# Grab a token (jq required):
#
#   TOKEN=$(curl -s -X POST localhost:8080/api/auth/login \
#     -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
#     -d '{"username":"alice","password":"S3cret!pass"}' | jq -r .token)
#
# Discover the contract (reflection is on in dev):
#
#   grpcurl -plaintext localhost:9090 list
#   grpcurl -plaintext localhost:9090 describe taskhub.notification.v1.NotificationService
#
# Subscribe — leave it running, then mutate a task over REST and watch events arrive:
#
#   grpcurl -plaintext -H "authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" -H 'x-correlation-id: my-subscriber' \
#     -d '{"project_id": "1"}' \
#     localhost:9090 taskhub.notification.v1.NotificationService/SubscribeTaskEvents
#
#   curl -X POST localhost:8080/api/projects/1/tasks \
#     -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
#     -H 'X-Correlation-Id: my-trace' \
#     -d '{"title":"Observe me","status":"TODO","priority":"HIGH"}'
#
# Publish a unary event by hand (the ack's delivered_to = open subscriptions reached,
# and is omitted from the JSON when it is zero):
#
#   grpcurl -plaintext -H "authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
#     -d '{"event_id":"manual-1","type":"TASK_CREATED","task_id":"1","project_id":"1",
#          "title":"Draft homepage copy","status":"TODO","actor":"alice"}' \
#     localhost:9090 taskhub.notification.v1.NotificationService/NotifyTaskEvent
#
# Unauthenticated → rejected by the auth interceptor:
#
#   grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"event_id":"forged"}' \
#     localhost:9090 taskhub.notification.v1.NotificationService/NotifyTaskEvent
#   # ERROR: Code: Unauthenticated  Message: A valid bearer token is required
#
# Health is exempt from auth, so probes keep working without a token:
#
#   grpcurl -plaintext localhost:9090 grpc.health.v1.Health/Check
#   # {"status":"SERVING"}
#
# Whatever you pass as x-correlation-id shows up in BOTH services' logs for that
# call — that is the point of the correlation-id interceptor.
